 Tipton]] (J)\n| Installed January 3, 1832\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Mississippi|Mississippi]]<br/>(1)\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Powhatan Ellis]] (J)\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned July 16, 1832, after being appointed [[United States District Court for the District of Mississippi|U.S. District Judge]].<br/>Successor appointed November 12, 1832, to finish the term.\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[John Black (U.S. Senator)|John Black]] (J)\n| Installed November 12, 1832\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Virginia|Virginia]]<br/>(2)\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Littleton Waller Tazewell]] (J)\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned July 16, 1832.<br/>Successor elected December 10, 1832.\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[William Cabell Rives|William C. Rives]] (J)\n| Installed December 10, 1832\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from South Carolina|South Carolina]]<br/>(2)\n| {{Party shading/Nullifier}} | [[Robert Y. Hayne]] (N)\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned December 13, 1832, to become [[Governor of South Carolina]].<br/>Successor elected December 29, 1832.\n| {{Party shading/Nullifier}} | [[John C. Calhoun]] (N)\n| Installed December 29, 1832\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from New York|New York]]<br/>(3)\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[William L. Marcy]] (J)\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned January 1, 1833, after becoming [[Governor of New York]].<br/>Successor elected January 14, 1833.\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Silas Wright]] (J)\n| Installed January 4, 1833\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from South Carolina|South Carolina]]<br/>(3)\n| {{Party shading/Nullifier}} | [[Stephen Decatur Miller|Stephen D. Miller]] (N)\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned March 2, 1833, due to ill health.\n| Vacant\n| Not filled this term\n|}\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n\n{{See also|List of special elections to the United States House of Representatives}}\n*replacements: 9\n** Jacksonians: 1-seat net gain\n** Anti-Jacksonians: 2-seat net loss\n** Anti-Masonics: 1-seat net gain\n* deaths: 8\n* resignations: 2\n* contested election: 0\n* '''Total seats with changes: 11'''\n\n<!--\nSorted Chronologically by date of vacancy\n-->\n{{Ordinal US Congress Rep}}\n|-\n| {{ushr|North Carolina|2|T}}\n| Vacant\n| Vacancy in term\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[John Branch]] (J)\n| Seated May 12, 1831\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Georgia|AL|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Wilson Lumpkin]] (J)\n| Resigned some time in 1831 before the convening of Congress\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Augustin Smith Clayton|Augustin S. Clayton]] (J)\n| Seated January 21, 1832\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Vermont|2|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[Rollin Carolas Mallary|Rollin C. Mallary]] (AJ)\n| Died April 15, 1831\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Masonic}} | [[William Slade]] (AM)\n| Seated November 1, 1831\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Missouri|AL|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[Spencer Darwin Pettis|Spencer D. Pettis]] (AJ)\n| Died August 28, 1831\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[William Henry Ashley|William H. Ashley]] (AJ)\n| Seated October 31, 1831\n|-\n| {{ushr|Pennsylvania|11|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[William Ramsey (Pennsylvania)|William Ramsey]] (J)\n| Died September 29, 1831\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Robert McCoy]] (J)\n| Seated November 22, 1831\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|North Carolina|6|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Robert Potter (U.S. politician)|Robert Potter]] (J)\n| Resigned November ????, 1831\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Micajah Thomas Hawkins|Micajah T. Hawkins]] (J)\n| Seated December 15, 1831\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Vermont|1|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[Jonathan Hunt (Vermont Representative)|Jonathan Hunt]] (AJ)\n| Died May 15, 1832.<br/>A [[1832\u20131833 Vermont's 1st congressional district special election|special election]] was held and a new member elected January 1, 1833 on the fourth ballot.\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[Hiland Hall]] (AJ)\n| Seated January 21, 1833\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|22|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Charles Clement Johnston|Charles C. Johnston]] (J)\n| Died June 17, 1832\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Joseph Draper]] (J)\n| Seated December 6, 1832\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Maryland|6|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[George Edward Mitchell|George E. Mitchell]] (J)\n| Died June 28, 1832\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Charles S. Sewall]] (J)\n| Seated October 1, 1832\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|18|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Anti-Jacksonian}} | [[Philip Doddridge (Virginia)|Philip Doddridge]] (AJ)\n| Died November 19, 1832\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[Joseph Johnson (Virginia politician)|Joseph Johnson]] (J)\n| Seated January 21, 1833\n\n|-\n| {{ushr|New York|1|T}}\n| {{Party shading/Jacksonian}} | [[James Lent]] (J)\n| Died February 22, 1833\n| Vacant\n| Not filled this Congress\n\n|}\n\n==Committees==\nLists of committees and their party leaders.\n\n===Senate===\n\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Accounts of James Monroe|Accounts of James Monroe]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Agriculture|Agriculture]] (Chairman: [[Horatio Seymour]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on Amending the Constitution on the Election of the President and Vice President|Amending the Constitution on the Election of the President and Vice President]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee to Audit and Control the Contingent Expenses of the Senate|Audit and Control the Contingent Expenses of the Senate]] (Chairman: [[Nehemiah Knight]])\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Claims|Claims]] (Chairman: [[Benjamin Ruggles]])\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Commerce|Commerce]] (Chairman: [[John Forsyth (Georgia)|John Forsyth]] then [[William R. King]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on Distributing Public Revenue Among the States|Distributing Public Revenue Among the States]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]] (Chairman: [[Ezekiel F. Chambers]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Dueling|Dueling]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Finance]] (Chairman: [[Samuel Smith (Maryland)|Samuel Smith]] then [[John Forsyth (Georgia)|John Forsyth]])\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Foreign Relations]] (Chairman: [[Littleton Tazewell]] then [[John Forsyth (Georgia)|John Forsyth]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on French Spoilations|French Spoilations]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Impeachment of James H. Peck|Impeachment of James H. Peck]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Indian Affairs|Indian Affairs]] (Chairman: N/A) \n* [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Judiciary]] (Chairman: [[William L. Marcy]] then [[William Wilkins (Tennessee politician)|William Wilkins]]) \n* [[United States Senate Committee on Manufactures|Manufactures]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Memorial of the Manufacturers Iron|Memorial of the Manufacturers Iron]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Mileage of Members of Congress|Mileage of Members of Congress]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Military Affairs|Military Affairs]] (Chairman: [[Thomas Hart Benton (politician)|Thomas Hart Benton]])\n* [[United States Senate Committee on the Militia|Militia]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Naval Affairs|Naval Affairs]] (Chairman: [[Robert Y. Hayne]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Nomination of Amos Kendall|Nomination of Amos Kendall]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Pensions|Pensions]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on Post Office Department|Post Office Department]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Post Office and Post Roads|Post Office and Post Roads]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Private Land Claims|Private Land Claims]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States Senate Committee on Public Lands|Public Lands]] (Chairman: [[William R. King]] then [[Elias Kane]])\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on Roads and Canals|Roads and Canals]] (Select)\n* [[United States Senate Select Committee on the Tariff Regulation|Tariff Regulation]] (Select)\n* [[Committee of the whole|Whole]]\n\n===House of Representatives===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Accounts|Accounts]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Agriculture]] (Chairman: [[Erastus Root]])\n* [[United States House Select Committee on the American Colonization Society|American Colonization Society]] (Select)\n* [[United States House Committee on Claims|Claims]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Commerce|Commerce]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Elections|Elections]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Select Committee on Establishing an Assay Office in the Gold Region|Establishing an Assay Office in the Gold Region]] (Select)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures in the Navy Department|Expenditures in the Navy Department]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures in the Post Office Department|Expenditures in the Post Office Department]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures in the State Department|Expenditures in the State Department]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures in the Treasury Department|Expenditures in the Treasury Department]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures in the War Department|Expenditures in the War Department]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Expenditures on Public Buildings|Expenditures on Public Buildings]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Foreign Affairs]] (Chairman: [[William S. Archer]])\n* [[United States House Committee on Indian Affairs|Indian Affairs]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Judiciary|Judiciary]] (Chairman: [[Warren R. Davis]] then [[John Bell]])\n* [[United States House Committee on Manufactures|Manufactures]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Military Affairs|Military Affairs]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Naval Affairs|Naval Affairs]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Post Office and Post Roads|Post Office and Post Roads]] (Chairman: [[Richard Mentor Johnson|Richard M. Johnson]] then [[Henry William Connor|Henry W. Connor]])\n* [[United States House Committee on Public Expenditures|Public Expenditures]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Public Lands|Public Lands]] (Chairman: [[Charles A. Wickliffe]])\n* [[United States House Committee on Revisal and Unfinished Business|Revisal and Unfinished Business]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Revolutionary Claims|Revolutionary Claims]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Select Committee on Rules|Rules]] (Select)\n* [[United States House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct|Standards of Official Conduct]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Territories|Territories]] (Chairman: N/A)\n* [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means]] (Chairman: [[George McDuffie]] then [[Gulian C. Verplanck]])\n* [[Committee of the Whole (United States House of Representatives)|Whole]]\n\n===Joint committees===\n\n* [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Enrolled Bills|Enrolled Bills]]\n\n== Employees ==\n* [[Librarian of Congress]]: [[John Silva Meehan]]\n\n=== Senate ===\n* [[Chaplain of the United States Senate|Chaplain]]: [[John P. Durbin]] ([[Methodism|Methodist]]), elected December 19, 1831\n** [[Charles C. Pise]] ([[Roman Catholic]]), elected December 11, 1832\n* [[Secretary of the United States Senate|Secretary]]: [[Walter Lowrie (politician)|Walter Lowrie]]\n* [[Sergeant at Arms of the United States Senate|Sergeant at Arms]]: [[Mountjoy Bayly]]\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n* [[Chaplain of the United States House of Representatives|Chaplain]]: [[Reuben Post]] ([[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]]) elected December 5, 1831\n** [[William Hammett]] ([[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]]), elected December 3, 1832\n* [[Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|Clerk]]: [[Matthew St. Clair Clarke]]\n* [[Doorkeeper of the United States House of Representatives|Doorkeeper]]: [[Overton Carr]], elected December 5, 1831\n* [[Reading Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|Reading Clerks]]: {{dm|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Sergeant at Arms of the United States House of Representatives|Sergeant at Arms]]: [[John O. Dunn]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1830 United States elections]] (elections leading to this Congress)\n** [[1830 and 1831 United States Senate elections]]\n** [[1830 and 1831 United States House of Representatives elections]]\n* [[1832 United States elections]] (elections during this Congress, leading to the next Congress)\n** [[1832 United States presidential election]]\n** [[1832 and 1833 United States Senate elections]]\n** [[1832 and 1833 United States House of Representatives elections]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book|title = The Historical Atlas of Political Parties in the United States Congress|last = Martis|first = Kenneth C.|authorlink =|coauthors =|year = 1989|publisher = Macmillan Publishing Company|location = New York|id =}}\n* {{cite book|title = The Historical Atlas of United States Congressional Districts|last = Martis|first = Kenneth C.|authorlink =|coauthors =|year = 1982|publisher = Macmillan Publishing Company|location = New York|id =}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/amlaw/lwsllink.html Statutes at Large, 1789-1875]\n* [http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/amlaw/lwsjlink.html Senate Journal, First Forty-three Sessions of Congress]\n* [http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/amlaw/lwhjlink.html#anchor2 House Journal, First Forty-three Sessions of Congress]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060601025644/http://www.gpoaccess.gov/serialset/cdocuments/hd108-222/index.html Biographical Directory of the U.S. Congress]\n* [http://clerk.house.gov/art_history/house_history/index.html U.S. House of Representatives: House History]\n* [https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/reference/two_column_table/stats_and_lists.htm U.S. Senate: Statistics and Lists]\n\n{{USCongresses}}\n\n[[Category:22nd United States Congress| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:John Bell\u2192John Bell (Tennessee politician)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/22nd_United_States_Congress"}
{"title_page": "Jack Vainisi", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jack Vainisi\n| image       = Jack Vainisi circa 1950s.png\n| alt         = Portrait photo of Jack Vainisi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1927|08|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1960|11|27|1927|08|27|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| occupation  = {{Ubl|Scout|Personnel director}}\n| spouse      = Jacqueline ({{Nee|McGinnis}}) Vainisi\n| relatives   = [[Jerry Vainisi]] <small>(brother)</small>\n| children    = 3\n| known_for   = Scout for the [[Green Bay Packers]]\n}}\n\n'''Jack Vainisi''' (August 27, 1927 &ndash; November 27, 1960) was an American [[Scout (sport)|scout]] and personnel director for the [[Green Bay Packers]] from 1950 to 1960. At the age of 23, he was hired by Packers head coach [[Gene Ronzani]] to lead the team's player personnel department. In a time when most professional football teams relied on the media for information on college players, Vainisi enlisted college coaches to provide scouting reports on not only their own players, but also opposition players. During his time in charge of player personnel, the Packers drafted or acquired eight future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] players. Vainisi also was instrumental in attracting [[Vince Lombardi]] to the vacant head coaching job in Green Bay in 1959. Vainisi did not live to see the success of the teams he helped assemble though, as he died from a heart attack in 1960 at the age of 33.\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\nJack Vainisi was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]] on August 27, 1927 to Anthony and Marie Vainisi.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/><ref name=\"HOF\"/> The Vainisi family, who lived on the North Side of Chicago, were strong supporters of the [[Chicago Bears]]. They ran a deli near [[Wrigley Field]], which at the time was the home of the Bears, that attracted many players.<ref name=\"MARIE\">{{cite web | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-05-05/news/0605050190_1_meals-jerry-vainisi-grocery | title = Marie Vainisi | last = Noel | first = Josh | date = May 5, 2006 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180214022415/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-05-05/news/0605050190_1_meals-jerry-vainisi-grocery | archive-date = February 14, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> Jack also attended grammar school with [[George Halas Jr.]], the son of Bears' coach [[George Halas]].{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}} The family was so ingrained in the Bears organization that a group of players came over to the Vainisi house every year for a home-cooked Italian meal by Marie.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/> In high school, Vainisi was an accomplished lineman on the football team and was offered an athletic scholarship to Notre Dame.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}}\n\nVainisi played for the [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame football team]] for one year.<ref name=\"HOF\"/> After his freshman year and near the end of [[World War II]], he was drafted into the Army and sent to Japan during the [[Occupation of Japan|post-war occupation]]. In Japan, he served in [[Douglas MacArthur|General Douglas MacArthur]]'s headquarters and played on a football team made up of service members.<ref name=\"OBIT1\">{{Cite news | title = Death Takes Officials Of Packers and Utility: Part 1| date = November 28, 1960| newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]| page = 1| via = [[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}}| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819954/vainisi_died_part_1/| access-date = October 24, 2018| archive-date = October 24, 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181025021340/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819954/vainisi_died_part_1/| url-status = live| df = mdy}}</ref> He became ill while in Japan, and after returning to America, was diagnosed with [[rheumatic fever]]. This condition caused permanent damage to his heart and precluded him from playing organized sports for the rest of his life.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}} After his military service, he returned to Notre Dame to complete his degree. He graduated in 1950 at the age of 23.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}\n\n==Green Bay Packers==\nWith some help from his family connections with the Chicago Bears, Vainisi was able to get a job with the [[Green Bay Packers]] shortly after graduating from Notre Dame. The Packers' new coach, [[Gene Ronzani]], had played for the Bears and dined at the Vainisi's, while Ronzani's assistant [[Hugh Devore]] coached Vainisi at Notre Dame. Vainisi was enthusiastic in his new role as a scout; professional scouting at the time was still in its infancy.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} Most team owners or head coaches would make player personnel decisions and would rely heavily on the media for scouting reports.<ref name=\"MJS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/columnists/gary-damato/2018/01/13/damato-packers-scout-jack-vainisi-deserves-lambeau-honor/1016324001/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] | date = January 13, 2018 | title = D'Amato: Packers scout Jack Vainisi deserves Lambeau Field honor | last = D'Amato | first = Gary | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/columnists/gary-damato/2018/01/13/damato-packers-scout-jack-vainisi-deserves-lambeau-honor/1016324001/ | archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> Vainisi quickly developed a large network of college coaches that would provide him scouting reports on football players. By the end of his career, he had reports on over 4,000 players that filled 18 notebooks, all of which were cross-referenced.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} For most of his career, Vainisi was the only professional scout the Packers had on staff.<ref name=\"PNEWS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/dougherty/2015/05/21/vainisi-starting-get-packers-due/27752263/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[USA Today]] | date = May 21, 2015 | title = Vainisi starting to get his Packers due | last = Dougherty | first = Pete | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912080220/http://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/dougherty/2015/05/21/vainisi-starting-get-packers-due/27752263/ | archive-date = August 12, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> He became well known around the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and respected for his knowledge, commitment, and scouting abilities.<ref name=\"OBIT2\">{{Cite news | title = Death Takes Officials Of Packers and Utility: Part 2| date = November 28, 1960| newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]| page = 2| via = [[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}}| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819971/vainisi_died_part_2/| access-date = October 24, 2018| archive-date = October 24, 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181025021408/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819971/vainisi_died_part_2/| url-status = live| df = mdy}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Packers' general manager retained the ultimate authority to draft and acquire players, Vainisi's reports and opinions were almost always followed.<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/> Over his ten-year career, Vainisi scouted and recommended drafting or acquiring eight future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]rs.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}}{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.profootballhof.com/heroes-of-the-game/franchises/ | title = Hall of Famers by Franchise | access-date = October 27, 2018 | publisher = [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181027163654/https://www.profootballhof.com/heroes-of-the-game/franchises/ | archive-date = October 27, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> The Packers [[1958 NFL Draft]] class is considered one of the best in history, as it included three Hall of Famers ([[Jim Taylor (fullback)|Jim Taylor]], [[Ray Nitschke]], and [[Jerry Kramer]]) and one all-pro ([[Dan Currie]]).<ref name=\"1958D\">{{cite web | url = http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/foundation-for-packers-titles-built-with-1958-nfl-draft-b99478181z1-299760811.html/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] | date = April 14, 2015 | title = Foundation for Packers' titles built with 1958 NFL draft | last = Hendricks | first = Martin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/foundation-for-packers-titles-built-with-1958-nfl-draft-b99478181z1-299760811.html/ | archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> Vainisi convinced the Packers to select future Hall of Famer [[Paul Hornung]] with the first pick of the [[1957 NFL Draft]] and drafted Hall of Famers [[Jim Ringo]], [[Bart Starr]] and [[Forrest Gregg]].<ref name=\"MJS\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=282}} Vainisi also signed [[Willie Wood (American football)|Willie Wood]] as a free agent in 1960.<ref name=\"MJS\"/> By the end of 1961, when the Packers won their first NFL Championship since 1944, 17 of the 22 offensive and defensive starters were acquired in some way by Vainisi.<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/>\n\nVainisi's greatest contribution to the Packers was his behind-the-scenes work in the hiring of Vince Lombardi in 1959.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/> Vainisi lobbied on Lombardi's behalf to team president [[Dominic Olejniczak]] and the board of directors of [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]].<ref name=\"MJS\"/> He also warned Lombardi to demand full control as coach and general manager to avoid interference by the directors in football decisions. During his interview, Lombardi stated to the board that he would not have considered Green Bay if it was not for Vainisi.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} With Lombardi at the helm, the Packers would go on to win five championships in seven years and over 100 games in the 1960s.<ref name=\"ProHof\">{{cite web |url= http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |title= NFL Champions |publisher= [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] |access-date= July 4, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001902/http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |archive-date= June 20, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"PFR\">{{cite web | title = Green Bay Packers Franchise Encyclopedia | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm | access-date = September 23, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm |archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVainisi married Jacqueline McGinnis in 1952.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} Jacqueline and Jack had three children: Valeria, Theresa, and Jack Anthony.<ref name=\"JACKIE\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=268}} In 1960, Vainisi suffered a massive heart attack and died at his home in Green Bay.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} Jacqueline was pregnant with their son at the time; Jack Anthony was delivered [[stillborn]] in January 1961, just a few months after his father died.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=268}} Jacqueline died in 2002 at the age of 75.<ref name=\"JACKIE\">{{cite web | url = http://www.genlookups.com/wi/webbbs_config.pl/noframes/read/83 | title = Wisconsin Obituary and Death Notice Archive | date = April 24, 2012 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | website = GenLookups.com | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170607150350/http://www.genlookups.com/wi/webbbs_config.pl/noframes/read/83 | archive-date = June 7, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref>\n\nJack's brother, [[Jerry Vainisi]], served as a  ball boy for the Packers throughout his youth. Jerry went on to work for the [[Chicago Bears]] for 15 years, serving on the board of directors and becoming the general manager from 1983 to 1986.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-11-03/sports/8503150403_1_forrest-gregg-jim-ringo-vince-lombardi | title = Brother`s Love Touches Rivalry | last = Verdi | first = Bob | date = November 3, 1985 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160326050408/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-11-03/sports/8503150403_1_forrest-gregg-jim-ringo-vince-lombardi | archive-date = March 26, 2016 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> He helped lead the Bears to a victory in [[Super Bowl XX]] in 1985.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFor all of his contributions to the successful Packers teams of the 1960s, Vainisi is not as well remembered as Lombardi or the players he brought to the team,<ref name=\"MJS\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} although at the time he was widely respected in the NFL.<ref name=\"OBIT2\"/> The newness of professional scouting in the 1960s and his relatively short life contributed to his diminished legacy.<ref name=\"MJS\"/> Even so, Vainisi's contributions to the Packers were significant, and he has been recognized throughout the years for his impact.<ref name=\"MJS\"/><ref name=\"PNEWS\"/><ref name=\"1958D\"/> Not only did Vainisi acquire eight future Pro Football Hall of Famers and many more core players, he was the primary reason that Lombardi took the head coaching job in Green Bay in 1959.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} Both the players and the new coach would go on to win five NFL championships, including three straight from 1965 to 1967, and the first two Super Bowls.<ref name=\"CHAMPS\">{{cite web |url= http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |title= NFL Champions |publisher= [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] |access-date= October 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001902/http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |archive-date= June 20, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> This success helped to resurrect an organization that had not had a winning season in 11 straight seasons during the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name=\"PFR\"/> In 1982, Vainisi was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in recognition for his contributions as a scout.<ref name=\"HOF\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packers.com/history/hof/jack-vainisi | title = Jack Vainisi | publisher = [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]] | last = Christl | first = Cliff | access-date = September 22, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.packers.com/history/hof/jack-vainisi | archive-date = October 26, 2018}}</ref> More recently, the Packers erected a monument honoring his legacy at the entrance to the [[Titletown District]], adjacent to Lambeau Field.<ref name=\"MONUMENT\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/05/19/vainisi-monument-groundbreaking-thursday-lambeau/27608481/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[USA Today]] | date = May 19, 2015 | title = Vainisi monument groundbreaking is Thursday | last = Ryman | first = Richard | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150622111632/http://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/05/19/vainisi-monument-groundbreaking-thursday-lambeau/27608481/ | archive-date = June 22, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"DEDICATED\">{{cite news | url = https://fox11online.com/news/local/green-bay/monument-honored-for-former-packers-talent-scout | title = Monument dedicated to key architect of Lombardi-era Packers | agency = Fox News 11 | date = July 29, 2015 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151019154121/http://fox11online.com/news/local/green-bay/monument-honored-for-former-packers-talent-scout | archive-date = October 19, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Maraniss | first = David | author-link = David Maraniss | year = 1999 | title = [[When Pride Still Mattered|When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi]] | publisher = Simon & Schuster | isbn = 978-0-618-90499-0 | ref = harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Findagrave|118628938}}\n\n{{Green Bay Packers HOF}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vainisi, Jack}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers scouts]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jack Vainisi\n| image       = Jack Vainisi circa 1950s.png\n| alt         = Portrait photo of Jack Vainisi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1927|08|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1960|11|27|1927|08|27|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| occupation  = {{Ubl|Scout|Personnel director}}\n| spouse      = Jacqueline ({{Nee|McGinnis}}) Vainisi\n| relatives   = [[Jerry Vainisi]] <small>(brother)</small>\n| children    = 3\n| known_for   = Scout for the [[Green Bay Packers]]\n}}\n\n'''Jack Vainisi''' (August 27, 1927 &ndash; November 27, 1960) was an American [[Scout (sport)|scout]] and personnel director for the [[Green Bay Packers]] from 1950 to 1960. At the age of 23, he was hired by Packers head coach [[Gene Ronzani]] to lead the team's player personnel department. In a time when most professional football teams relied on the media for information on college players, Vainisi enlisted college coaches to provide scouting reports on not only their own players, but also opposition players. During his time in charge of player personnel, the Packers drafted or acquired eight future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] players. Vainisi also was instrumental in attracting [[Vince Lombardi]] to the vacant head coaching job in Green Bay in 1959. Vainisi did not live to see the success of the teams he helped assemble though, as he died from a heart attack in 1960 at the age of 33.\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\nJack Vainisi was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]] on August 27, 1927 to Anthony and Marie Vainisi.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/><ref name=\"HOF\"/> The Vainisi family, who lived on the North Side of Chicago, were strong supporters of the [[Chicago Bears]]. They ran a deli near [[Wrigley Field]], which at the time was the home of the Bears, that attracted many players.<ref name=\"MARIE\">{{cite web | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-05-05/news/0605050190_1_meals-jerry-vainisi-grocery | title = Marie Vainisi | last = Noel | first = Josh | date = May 5, 2006 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180214022415/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-05-05/news/0605050190_1_meals-jerry-vainisi-grocery | archive-date = February 14, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> Jack also attended grammar school with [[George Halas Jr.]], the son of Bears' coach [[George Halas]].{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}} The family was so ingrained in the Bears organization that a group of players came over to the Vainisi house every year for a home-cooked Italian meal by Marie.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/> In high school, Vainisi was an accomplished lineman on the football team and was offered an athletic scholarship to Notre Dame.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}}\n\nVainisi played for the [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame football team]] for one year.<ref name=\"HOF\"/> After his freshman year and near the end of [[World War II]], he was drafted into the Army and sent to Japan during the [[Occupation of Japan|post-war occupation]]. In Japan, he served in [[Douglas MacArthur|General Douglas MacArthur]]'s headquarters and played on a football team made up of service members.<ref name=\"OBIT1\">{{Cite news | title = Death Takes Officials Of Packers and Utility: Part 1| date = November 28, 1960| newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]| page = 1| via = [[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}}| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819954/vainisi_died_part_1/| access-date = October 24, 2018| archive-date = October 24, 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181025021340/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819954/vainisi_died_part_1/| url-status = live| df = mdy}}</ref> He became ill while in Japan, and after returning to America, was diagnosed with [[rheumatic fever]]. This condition caused permanent damage to his heart and precluded him from playing organized sports for the rest of his life.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}} After his military service, he returned to Notre Dame to complete his degree. He graduated in 1950 at the age of 23.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}\n\n==Green Bay Packers==\nWith some help from his family connections with the Chicago Bears, Vainisi was able to get a job with the [[Green Bay Packers]] shortly after graduating from Notre Dame. The Packers' new coach, [[Gene Ronzani]], had played for the Bears and dined at the Vainisi's, while Ronzani's assistant [[Hugh Devore]] coached Vainisi at Notre Dame. Vainisi was enthusiastic in his new role as a scout; professional scouting at the time was still in its infancy.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} Most team owners or head coaches would make player personnel decisions and would rely heavily on the media for scouting reports.<ref name=\"MJS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/columnists/gary-damato/2018/01/13/damato-packers-scout-jack-vainisi-deserves-lambeau-honor/1016324001/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] | date = January 13, 2018 | title = D'Amato: Packers scout Jack Vainisi deserves Lambeau Field honor | last = D'Amato | first = Gary | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/columnists/gary-damato/2018/01/13/damato-packers-scout-jack-vainisi-deserves-lambeau-honor/1016324001/ | archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> Vainisi quickly developed a large network of college coaches that would provide him scouting reports on football players. By the end of his career, he had reports on over 4,000 players that filled 18 notebooks, all of which were cross-referenced.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} For most of his career, Vainisi was the only professional scout the Packers had on staff.<ref name=\"PNEWS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/dougherty/2015/05/21/vainisi-starting-get-packers-due/27752263/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[USA Today]] | date = May 21, 2015 | title = Vainisi starting to get his Packers due | last = Dougherty | first = Pete | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912080220/http://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/dougherty/2015/05/21/vainisi-starting-get-packers-due/27752263/ | archive-date = August 12, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> He became well known around the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and respected for his knowledge, commitment, and scouting abilities.<ref name=\"OBIT2\">{{Cite news | title = Death Takes Officials Of Packers and Utility: Part 2| date = November 28, 1960| newspaper = [[Green Bay Press-Gazette]]| page = 2| via = [[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}}| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819971/vainisi_died_part_2/| access-date = October 24, 2018| archive-date = October 24, 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181025021408/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24819971/vainisi_died_part_2/| url-status = live| df = mdy}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Packers' general manager retained the ultimate authority to draft and acquire players, Vainisi's reports and opinions were almost always followed.<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/> Over his ten-year career, Vainisi scouted and recommended drafting or acquiring eight future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]rs.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=250}}{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.profootballhof.com/heroes-of-the-game/franchises/ | title = Hall of Famers by Franchise | access-date = October 27, 2018 | publisher = [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181027163654/https://www.profootballhof.com/heroes-of-the-game/franchises/ | archive-date = October 27, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> The Packers [[1958 NFL Draft]] class is considered one of the best in history, as it included three Hall of Famers ([[Jim Taylor (fullback)|Jim Taylor]], [[Ray Nitschke]], and [[Jerry Kramer]]) and one all-pro ([[Dan Currie]]).<ref name=\"1958D\">{{cite web | url = http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/foundation-for-packers-titles-built-with-1958-nfl-draft-b99478181z1-299760811.html/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] | date = April 14, 2015 | title = Foundation for Packers' titles built with 1958 NFL draft | last = Hendricks | first = Martin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/foundation-for-packers-titles-built-with-1958-nfl-draft-b99478181z1-299760811.html/ | archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref> Vainisi convinced the Packers to select future Hall of Famer [[Paul Hornung]] with the first pick of the [[1957 NFL Draft]] and drafted Hall of Famers [[Jim Ringo]], [[Bart Starr]] and [[Forrest Gregg]].<ref name=\"MJS\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=282}} Vainisi also signed [[Willie Wood (American football)|Willie Wood]] as a free agent in 1960.<ref name=\"MJS\"/> By the end of 1961, when the Packers won their first NFL Championship since 1944, 17 of the 22 offensive and defensive starters were acquired in some way by Vainisi.<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/>\n\nVainisi's greatest contribution to the Packers was his behind-the-scenes work in the hiring of Vince Lombardi in 1959.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}<ref name=\"PNEWS\"/> Vainisi lobbied on Lombardi's behalf to team president [[Dominic Olejniczak]] and the [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]] board of directors.<ref name=\"MJS\"/> He also warned Lombardi to demand full control as coach and general manager to avoid interference by the Directors in football decisions. During his interview, Lombardi stated to the board that he would not have considered Green Bay if it was not for Vainisi.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} With Lombardi at the helm, the Packers would go on to win five championships in seven years and over 100 games in the 1960s.<ref name=\"ProHof\">{{cite web |url= http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |title= NFL Champions |publisher= [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] |access-date= July 4, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001902/http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |archive-date= June 20, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"PFR\">{{cite web | title = Green Bay Packers Franchise Encyclopedia | publisher = Sports Reference LLC | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm | access-date = September 23, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/gnb/index.htm |archive-date = October 26, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVainisi married Jacqueline McGinnis in 1952.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}} Jacqueline and Jack had three children: Valeria, Theresa, and Jack Anthony.<ref name=\"JACKIE\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=268}} In 1960, Vainisi suffered a massive heart attack and died at his home in Green Bay.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} Jacqueline was pregnant with their son at the time; Jack Anthony was delivered [[stillborn]] in January 1961, just a few months after his father died.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=268}} Jacqueline died in 2002 at the age of 75.<ref name=\"JACKIE\">{{cite web | url = http://www.genlookups.com/wi/webbbs_config.pl/noframes/read/83 | title = Wisconsin Obituary and Death Notice Archive | date = April 24, 2012 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | website = GenLookups.com | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170607150350/http://www.genlookups.com/wi/webbbs_config.pl/noframes/read/83 | archive-date = June 7, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref>\n\nJack's brother, [[Jerry Vainisi]], served as a  ball boy for the Packers throughout his youth. Jerry went on to work for the [[Chicago Bears]] for 15 years, serving on the board of directors and becoming the general manager from 1983 to 1986.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-11-03/sports/8503150403_1_forrest-gregg-jim-ringo-vince-lombardi | title = Brother`s Love Touches Rivalry | last = Verdi | first = Bob | date = November 3, 1985 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | newspaper = [[Chicago Tribune]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160326050408/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-11-03/sports/8503150403_1_forrest-gregg-jim-ringo-vince-lombardi | archive-date = March 26, 2016 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref> He helped lead the Bears to a victory in [[Super Bowl XX]] in 1985.<ref name=\"MARIE\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFor all of his contributions to the successful Packers teams of the 1960s, Vainisi is not as well remembered as Lombardi or the players he brought to the team,<ref name=\"MJS\"/>{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} although at the time he was widely respected in the NFL.<ref name=\"OBIT2\"/> The newness of professional scouting in the 1960s and his relatively short life contributed to his diminished legacy.<ref name=\"MJS\"/> Even so, Vainisi's contributions to the Packers were significant, and he has been recognized throughout the years for his impact.<ref name=\"MJS\"/><ref name=\"PNEWS\"/><ref name=\"1958D\"/> Not only did Vainisi acquire eight future Pro Football Hall of Famers and many more core players, he was the primary reason that Lombardi took the head coaching job in Green Bay in 1959.{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=251}}{{sfn|Maraniss|1999|p=249}} Both the players and the new coach would go on to win five NFL championships, including three straight from 1965 to 1967, and the first two Super Bowls.<ref name=\"CHAMPS\">{{cite web |url= http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |title= NFL Champions |publisher= [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] |access-date= October 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001902/http://www.profootballhof.com/nfl-champions/ |archive-date= June 20, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> This success helped to resurrect an organization that had not had a winning season in 11 straight seasons during the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name=\"PFR\"/> In 1982, Vainisi was inducted into the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]] in recognition for his contributions as a scout.<ref name=\"HOF\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packers.com/history/hof/jack-vainisi | title = Jack Vainisi | publisher = [[Green Bay Packers, Inc.]] | last = Christl | first = Cliff | access-date = September 22, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026192426/https://www.packers.com/history/hof/jack-vainisi | archive-date = October 26, 2018}}</ref> More recently, the Packers erected a monument honoring his legacy at the entrance to the [[Titletown District]], adjacent to Lambeau Field.<ref name=\"MONUMENT\">{{cite web | url = https://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/05/19/vainisi-monument-groundbreaking-thursday-lambeau/27608481/ | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[USA Today]] | date = May 19, 2015 | title = Vainisi monument groundbreaking is Thursday | last = Ryman | first = Richard | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150622111632/http://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/05/19/vainisi-monument-groundbreaking-thursday-lambeau/27608481/ | archive-date = June 22, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"DEDICATED\">{{cite news | url = https://fox11online.com/news/local/green-bay/monument-honored-for-former-packers-talent-scout | title = Monument dedicated to key architect of Lombardi-era Packers | agency = Fox News 11 | date = July 29, 2015 | access-date = August 27, 2018 | publisher = [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151019154121/http://fox11online.com/news/local/green-bay/monument-honored-for-former-packers-talent-scout | archive-date = October 19, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Maraniss | first = David | author-link = David Maraniss | year = 1999 | title = [[When Pride Still Mattered|When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi]] | publisher = Simon & Schuster | isbn = 978-0-618-90499-0 | ref = harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Findagrave|118628938}}\n\n{{Green Bay Packers HOF}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vainisi, Jack}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers scouts]]\n", "name_user": "Gonzo fan2007", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGreen Bay Packers:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Vainisi"}
{"title_page": "Anastasios Kyriakos", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tasos Kyriakos\n| image = TasosKyriakos.jpg\n| fullname = Anastasios Kyriakos\n| height = {{height|m=1.77}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1978|8|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Giannouli]], [[Larissa (regional unit)|Larissa]], [[Greece]]\n| currentclub = AS Ano Meras\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]], [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 = Pelasgiotida\n| years1 = 1997\u20131999 | clubs1 =  [[Apollon Larissa F.C.|Apollon Larissa]] | caps1 = 8   | goals1 = 0     \n| years2 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs2 =  [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                 | caps2 = 31  | goals2 = 3   \n| years3 = 2002\u20132005 | clubs3 =  [[Kallithea F.C.|Kallithea]]             | caps3 = 75  | goals3 = 9   \n| years4 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs4 =  [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]             | caps4 = 0   | goals4 = 0   \n| years5 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs5 =  [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]]            | caps5 = 13  | goals5 = 1     \n| years6 = 2008      | clubs6 =  [[PAE Asteras Tripolis|Asteras Tripolis]]  | caps6 = 6   | goals6 = 0    \n| years7 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs7 =  [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                       | caps7 = 23  | goals7 = 0     \n| years8 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs8 =  [[AC Omonoia]]                             | caps8 = 5   | goals8 = 0 \n| years9 = 2010\u20132012 | clubs9 =  [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]         | caps9 = 45  | goals9 = 6\n| years10 = 2012\u20132013| clubs10 = [[Niki Volos F.C.|Niki Volos]]             | caps10 = 36 | goals10 = 4  \n| years11 = 2013\u20132014| clubs11 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]]      | caps11 = 7  | goals11 = 2\n| years12 = 2014     | clubs12 = [[Paniliakos F.C.|Paniliakos]]             | caps12 = 8  | goals12 = 4\n| years13 = 2014     | clubs13 = [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon Smyrni]]     | caps13 = 11 | goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2015     | clubs14 = [[Tyrnavos 2005 F.C.|Tyrnavos]]            | caps14 = 18 | goals14 = 0\n| years15 = 2016\u20132017| clubs15 = [[Apollon Larissa F.C.|Apollon Larissa]]   | caps15 =    | goals15 = \n| years16 = 2017\u20132018   | clubs16 = [[Asteras Amaliada F.C.|Asteras Amaliada]] | caps16 = 19 | goals16 = 1\n| years17 = 2018   | clubs17 = Aetos Makrychori | caps17 = 2 | goals17 = 0\n| years18 = 2018\u20132019   | clubs18 = Diagoras Stefanovikiou | caps18 =  | goals18 = \n| years19 = 2019\u2013   | clubs19 = AS Ano Meras| caps19 =  | goals19 = \n| nationalyears1 =  \n| nationalteam1 =  \n| nationalcaps1 =    \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = 3 October 2018\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Tasos Kyriakos''' ({{lang-el|\u03a4\u03ac\u03c3\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2}}; born 14 August 1978) is a [[Greece|Greek]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who plays for amateur club AS Ano Meras, as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] or [[midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Giannouli]], [[Larissa (regional unit)|Larissa]], Kyriakos started his career at his hometown with [[Apollon Larissa F.C.|Apollon Larissa]] and he later moved to the local giants [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]], then playing in [[Beta Ethniki]].\n\nSince 2002 he has been playing in the [[Super League Greece|Greek First Division]], as a member of [[Kallithea F.C.|Kallithea]], [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]], [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]], [[PAE Asteras Tripolis|Asteras Tripolis]] and again AEL, where he returned on 25 August 2008 and played for one season. On 15 July 2013 he signed an annual contract with [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Iraklis F.C. |url=http://www.fciraklis.gr/nea/press/item/572-%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%B4%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%86%CE%B1%CE%B9%CF%81%CE%B9%CF%83%CF%84%CE%AE%CF%82-%CF%84%CE%BF%CF%85-%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%B1%CE%BA%CE%BB%CE%B7-%CE%BF-%CF%84%CE%AC%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%82-%CE%BA%CF%85%CF%81%CE%B9%CE%AC%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%82 |script-title=el:\u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0397\u03a1\u0391\u039a\u039b\u0397 \u03bf \u03a4\u03ac\u03c3\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 |date=15 July 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013 |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718141432/http://www.fciraklis.gr/nea/press/item/572-%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%B4%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%86%CE%B1%CE%B9%CF%81%CE%B9%CF%83%CF%84%CE%AE%CF%82-%CF%84%CE%BF%CF%85-%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%B1%CE%BA%CE%BB%CE%B7-%CE%BF-%CF%84%CE%AC%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%82-%CE%BA%CF%85%CF%81%CE%B9%CE%AC%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%82 |archivedate=18 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> In January 2014, Kyriakos signed a contract with [[Football League (Greece)|Greek Football League]] club [[Paniliakos F.C.]].\n\nThe transfer from Kallithea F.C. to Olympiacos F.C. was by some seen as a surprise move despite the fact that Olympiacos F.C. had competition for the signature of the player. Rumors in the Greek media, Ethnospor among others, claimed that Br\u00f8ndby IF and their head coach Michael Laudrup expressed their interest in Kyriakos just before Olympiacos F.C. signed him.\n\n==Honours==\n'''[[AC Omonia|Omonia]]'''\n*[[Cypriot First Division|Cypriot Championship]]: [[Cypriot First Division 2009-10|2009\u201310]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerway}}\n*[http://www.onsports.gr/onstats/?url=/soccer/player/main.php&sport-select=soccer&player-select=531 Profile] at Onsports.gr\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140101100901/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=444 Myplayer.gr Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyriakos, Anastasios}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Larissa]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC players]]\n[[Category:Kallithea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aris Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Asteras Tripoli F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Niki Volou FC players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Paniliakos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Apollon Smyrni F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Greece-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tasos Kyriakos\n| image = TasosKyriakos.jpg\n| fullname = Anastasios Kyriakos\n| height = {{height|m=1.77}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1978|8|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Giannouli]], [[Larissa (regional unit)|Larissa]], [[Greece]]\n| currentclub = AS Ano Meras\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]], [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 = Pelasgiotida\n| years1 = 1997\u20131999 | clubs1 =  [[Apollon Larissa F.C.|Apollon Larissa]] | caps1 = 8   | goals1 = 0     \n| years2 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs2 =  [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                 | caps2 = 31  | goals2 = 3   \n| years3 = 2002\u20132005 | clubs3 =  [[Kallithea F.C.|Kallithea]]             | caps3 = 75  | goals3 = 9   \n| years4 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs4 =  [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]             | caps4 = 0   | goals4 = 0   \n| years5 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs5 =  [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]]            | caps5 = 13  | goals5 = 1     \n| years6 = 2008      | clubs6 =  [[PAE Asteras Tripolis|Asteras Tripolis]]  | caps6 = 6   | goals6 = 0    \n| years7 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs7 =  [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                       | caps7 = 23  | goals7 = 0     \n| years8 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs8 =  [[AC Omonoia]]                             | caps8 = 5   | goals8 = 0 \n| years9 = 2010\u20132012 | clubs9 =  [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]         | caps9 = 45  | goals9 = 6